---
/**
 * Hub: hourly ↔ salary conversion. Worked example computed by hourlyToSalary().
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import HourlySalaryConverter from '../../components/calculators/HourlySalaryConverter.tsx';
import { hourlyToSalary } from '../../lib/wage';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const base = hourlyToSalary(30, 40, 52);
const withUnpaid = hourlyToSalary(30, 40, 50, 1.5, 0, 2);
---

<Base
  title="Hourly to salary calculator — convert your wage (2026)"
  description="Convert an hourly wage to annual, monthly and weekly salary, or a salary back to an hourly rate. Accounts for overtime hours and unpaid weeks off."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">Wage conversion</p>
    <h1>Hourly to salary calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">What an hourly rate works out to across a year — and what a salary is really worth per hour.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    The quick version of this conversion — rate times 2,080 hours — assumes 40
    paid hours every week of the year. Real years have unpaid weeks, overtime, and
    schedules that are not 40 hours. This does the conversion both directions and
    lets you say how many weeks you are actually paid for.
  </p>

  <HourlySalaryConverter client:load direction="toSalary" />

  <h2>Worked example — {formatMoney(30)} an hour, full time</h2>
  <p>
    At {formatMoney(30)} an hour, 40 hours a week, every week of the year, the
    annual figures are:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Period</th><th>Amount</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Per year</td><td>{formatMoney(base.annual)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Per month</td><td>{formatMoney(base.monthly)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Every two weeks</td><td>{formatMoney(base.biweekly)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Per week</td><td>{formatMoney(base.weekly)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Take two weeks of unpaid leave — 50 paid weeks instead of 52 — and the same
    {formatMoney(30)} rate annualizes to {formatMoney(withUnpaid.annual)} rather
    than {formatMoney(base.annual)}. The difference, {formatMoney(base.annual - withUnpaid.annual)},
    is exactly two weeks of pay, and it is the gap the naive 2,080-hour formula
    hides.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How do I convert hourly to salary?</h3>
    <p>
      Multiply your hourly rate by hours worked per week, then by the number of
      weeks you are paid. The common shorthand is rate × 2,080 (40 hours × 52
      weeks), but that overstates pay if you take unpaid time. This calculator
      lets you set both figures.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What salary is $30 an hour?</h3>
    <p>
      About {formatMoney(base.annual)} a year at 40 hours a week for 52 weeks,
      before tax. Fewer paid weeks or fewer hours lowers it; regular overtime
      raises it. The figure here is gross — for take-home after federal, FICA and
      state tax, use the <a href="/paycheck-calculator/">paycheck calculator</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does this include overtime?</h3>
    <p>
      It can. Add your typical overtime hours per week and the multiplier, and
      they are annualized alongside your regular hours. The blended-rate line
      shows what every hour averaged out to once overtime is counted.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How do I convert a salary back to an hourly rate?</h3>
    <p>
      Switch the calculator to salary-to-hourly and enter your annual pay plus
      your real hours and weeks. A {formatMoney(base.annual)} salary at 40 hours
      over 52 weeks is {formatMoney(30)} an hour — but if that salary quietly
      expects 50-hour weeks, the true rate is lower, which is the point of doing
      the math.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Is a salary better than the same money hourly?</h3>
    <p>
      It depends on hours and overtime rights. Salaried exempt roles are not paid
      for extra hours; non-exempt and hourly roles are. Convert both to a blended
      hourly rate at the hours you actually expect to work, then compare.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/overtime-pay-calculator/">Overtime pay calculator</a> — a week of daily hours</li>
    <li><a href="/paycheck-calculator/">Paycheck calculator</a> — take-home from a salary</li>
    <li><a href="/raise-calculator/">Raise calculator</a> — compare an old and new rate</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Gross figures for the 2026 tax year, before any tax or deduction. Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
